{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://digbmc.github.io/pta-manifests/phan/phan-02536/manifest.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"none":["PHAN-02536"]},"metadata":[{"label":{"none":["Timestamp"]},"value":{"none":["0:25:36"]}},{"label":{"none":["Film"]},"value":{"none":["Phantom Thread"]}},{"label":{"none":["Creator"]},"value":{"none":["Paul Thomas Anderson"]}},{"label":{"none":["Distance"]},"value":{"none":["full shot"]}},{"label":{"none":["Angle"]},"value":{"none":["low"]}},{"label":{"none":["Location"]},"value":{"none":["interior"]}},{"label":{"none":["Movement"]},"value":{"none":["fixed"]}},{"label":{"none":["Composition"]},"value":{"none":["two shot"]}}],"summary":{"none":["A man examines a dress he is tailoring."]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02536/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"homepage":[{"id":"PHAN-02536","type":"Text","format":"text/html","label":{"none":["Object homepage"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02536/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","height":1080,"width":1920,"label":{"none":["PHAN-02536"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02536/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02536/canvas/1/annopage-1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02536/canvas/1/annopage-1/anno-1","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02536/canvas/1","body":{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02536/tiles/full/1920,1080/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02536/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02536/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02536/canvas/1/8ccaca6d-bda9-4e77-a4a4-186490717bed","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-29T14:08:49.819Z","creator":"grace","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>According to PTA, <em>Phantom Thread</em> was the result of several motivations: “How many more films do I have left to make? Time’s running out. I had a desire to make a film in England, and an appreciation for couture and those gowns and that kind of world, and the genre of Gothic romance that was so appealing to me, too. And I’ll name-drop: Chris Rock once said to me, ‘Man, when are you gonna make a relationship movie?’ I was like, ‘Hmm, that’s a good one.’ If Chris Rock gives you a piece of advice, you should run with it” (Buchanan, “<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW34288776 BCX4\" href=\"https://www.vulture.com/2017/12/director-paul-thomas-anderson-on-phantom-thread-mortality.html\"><u>Love, Death, and Control</u></a>”). One might argue that <em>Punch-Drunk Love</em>, at least, is also a “relationship movie.” The difference, perhaps, is that the 2002 film is very much the story of Barry Egan, while <em>Phantom Thread</em> is the story of both Reynolds and Alma, even if we don’t learn much of their backstories, particularly that of Alma.&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02536/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:85.27590847913868,54.83176312247647,344.97981157469724,326.89098250336474"}}}]}]}]}